To generate a table of contents automatically in a LaTeX document, you will have to use the `\tableofcontents` command. Here's an example:

```latex
\documentclass{article}

\begin{document}

\title{My First Document}
\author{Your Name}
\date{\today}

\maketitle

\tableofcontents

\section{Introduction}
This is where you will provide an introduction.

\section{Method}
This is where you will describe your method.

\subsection{Step 1}
This is the first step.

\subsection{Step 2}
This is the second step.

\section{Results}
This is where you will present your results.

\section{Conclusion}
This is where you will provide a conclusion.

\end{document}
```

In this example, the `\section` and `\subsection` commands are used to create sections and subsections in the document. The `\tableofcontents` command is placed after the `\maketitle` command and before the first section. 

When this LaTeX document is compiled, a table of contents will be generated automatically at the place where `\tableofcontents` is located. The table of contents will list the names of the sections and subsections along with their respective page numbers.

Please note that you may need to compile your document twice for the table of contents to update correctly. The first compilation generates the auxiliary files and the second compilation incorporates this information into the document.

Also, remember that LaTeX is case sensitive, so make sure to write the commands exactly as shown.

