Sure, here is a Java solution using a loop for the given problem. This solution checks whether the number is a power of three by continuously dividing it by three until it can't be divided anymore, then checks if the result is one.

```java
public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        System.out.println(isPowerOfThree(27));  // true
        System.out.println(isPowerOfThree(0));   // false
        System.out.println(isPowerOfThree(-1));  // false
    }

    public static boolean isPowerOfThree(int n) {
        if (n < 1) {
            return false;
        }

        while (n % 3 == 0) {
            n /= 3;
        }

        return n == 1;
    }
}
```

To solve the problem without using loops or recursion, we can use the properties of integers and logarithms. We know that the maximum power of 3 that integer can hold is 3^19 = 1162261467. So, we simply need to check if the number divides 1162261467. If it does, then we know it is a power of 3.

```java
public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        System.out.println(isPowerOfThree(27));  // true
        System.out.println(isPowerOfThree(0));   // false
        System.out.println(isPowerOfThree(-1));  // false
    }

    public static boolean isPowerOfThree(int n) {
        return n > 0 && 1162261467 % n == 0;
    }
}
```

In both of the above solutions, the time complexity is O(1) and the space complexity is also O(1).

